        <section xml:id="Section_2_3">
        <title>Section 2.3</title>
        

<subsection xml:id="Question_2_3_2">
    <title> Problem 2</title>
    <ol marker="(a)">  
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>a|b</m>, there exists <m>s</m> such that <m>as=b</m>. Then <m>asc=bc=a(sc)=bc</m> so <m>a|bc</m>.
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>a|b</m> and <m>a|c</m> then there exist integers <m>s,t</m> such that <m>as=b</m> and <m>at=c</m>. Multiply these two equations: <m>a^2st=a^2(st)=bc</m>, so <m>a^2|bc</m>.
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>a|b</m> then <m>as=b</m> for some integer <m>s</m>. Then <m>asc=ac(s)=bc</m> so <m>ac|bc</m>. Conversely, if <m>ac|bc</m> then <m>act=bc</m> for some integer <m>t</m>. Divide by <m>c</m> to obtain <m>at=b</m>, so <m>a|b</m>.
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                similar
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</subsection>        

<subsection xml:id="Question_2_3_3">
    <title> Problem 3</title>
    <p>
        This is false.  For example: <m>a=5, b=2, c=3</m>.
    </p>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="Question_2_3_5">
    <title> Problem 5</title>
    <p>
        By the division algorithm, <m>a=3q</m>, <m>a=3q+1</m>, or <m>a=3q+2</m>. 
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>a=3q</m>, then <m>3|a</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>a=3q+1</m>, then <m>a+2=3q+3=3(a+1)</m>, and <m>3|(a+2)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>a=3q+2</m>, then <m>a+4=3q+6=3(q+2)</m>, and <m>3|(a+4)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="Question_2_3_12">
    <title> Problem 12</title>
    <p> Let <m>d=\text{gcd}(a, a+n).</m> We'll use Theorem 2.2(g):
        <m>d|a</m> and <m>d|(a+n)</m> so <m>d|(a+n)-a</m>, that is <m>d|n</m>.  With <m>n=1</m> we have <m>\text{gcd}(a, a+1)|1</m> so it must be that <m>\text{gcd}(a,a+1)=1.</m>
    </p>
</subsection>
     

